rComments: This guy talks a lot, but says nothing of value. A severe lack of concrete information. Most classes I barely take any notes because he is digressing so far into obscurity.  SO BORING. Chosen material is so dull... The Perfect Enjoyment wasn't even on the syllabus... he needs to brighten up. UOttawa needs to fire him to make way for inspiring profs
I had Frans for a grad course. I liked him. The material wasn't the most stimulating, but he did a good job of delineating concepts, generating discussion and provoking thought.

he's not a big fan of opposing opinions. at the beginning of the course i'd write my own perspective (which was always diff than his) and i'd get a C. Then i learned if i can figure out what he likes to hear you'll end up with an A. He's also not kind to minorities in class. it's very very very obvious. write what he wants to hear. that's all.

One of those gems who will give you an A if you spout his own tripe back at him.  If you decide to show your own creativity or intelligence, you'll end up with a C.  He talks down to his students and if you're a visible minority or a person with poor english skills, he'll flaunt it in front of the class. Why he is still employed is beyond me.

A day class with him makes you sleepy, and a night class puts you in a coma.  I'll never get those hours back.  Nice, and knows his stuff, but god forbid you don't write your essay exactly in the format you want.  You'll be smacked with a C faster than you can say, "Please, god, not more Swift!"

When I just fed his stuff back to him I got an A, when I tried to be creative, I got a C. No style errors, just disagreed with my reading. Ridiculous to mark undergrads on basis of agreement and not strength of argument which he didn't question.
He's a decent guy but I found him irritable.  I got the impression that he didn't always like his job.  But, he knows his subject very well and I recommend taking "The Rise of the Novel" with him.
Tall, booming voice, nice dresser. Hard marker, boring material, thorough exams, but he conveyed it all very well.
